    <section id="concept">
        <div class="row">
            <div class="span12">
                <div class="event-panel">
                    <h2>Concept</h2>
                    <p>Open Data is the idea that certain data (non-personal) should be freely available to everyone to use and republish as they wish, without restrictions from copyright, patents or other control mechanisms. The value of this idea is that it improves transparency (What are my taxes being spent on?), it can optimize existing industries (What should hospitals specialize in?), or create new ones (How do public transport providers get me from A to B?).</p>
                    <p>At Make.01 we'll write applications, liberate data, create visualizations and publish analyses using open data to show support for and encourage the adoption of open data policies.</p>
                    
                    <h3>Who is this for?</h3>
                    <p>Developers get crafty at hackathons, service designers have their 'Global Jam', Data Scientists route cars at Traffic Camp, and entrepreneurs launch ideas over a StartUp Weekend. For many disciplines and niches, there are events where over the course of the weekend attendees learn about or develop something in their niche. Make.01 is all that, but isn't restricted or reducible to a formula like 'Business + Design + Technology'.
                    <p>Open Data can be sourced and built on in any domain or industry, so this event is open to anyone who has an idea for using open data, wants to find an interesting project to contribute towards, learn about how to visualize or analyse data or simply want to see what's happening.</p>
                    <p>OpenData is a truly cross-disciplinary affair so that's why we expect that Developers, Statisticians, Journalists, Designers, and Citizens alike will each contribute their skills to the projects at Make.01</p>
                    <img class="col-image" src="http://assets.okfn.org/images/data-types.png">
                    <h3>How will it work?</h3>
                    <p>Make.01 is a weekend where people with complementary skill-sets team up to make with and for Open Data. We'll hold a Catalyst night on the Tuesday before the event, so all participants are introduced to each other and everyone gets a chance to pitch their project ideas for the weekend.</p>
                    <p>We'll do some complex number crunching and people polling and come up with a list of projects which have sufficient people behind them to be feasibly made over a weekend. Projects can be merged if sufficiently similar. People are then free to join the teams of their choosing. We'll do a final round to confirm which projects have teams rallied behind them. To accommodate those projects which are one-person/few hours projects, we'll keep the schedule flexible, and spread them over the course of the weekend.</p>
                    <p>You'll be able to submit and review project proposals on this page as soon as the submission system goes live.</p>
                    <p>Between the catalyst night and the weekend, makers will have the opportunity to sharpen their pencils, setup their development environments, and generally get the more mundane setup stage over with prior to the event.</p>
                    <p>Over the weekend the teams will work on their respective projects. Since some projects will be completed within hours, and some short-trackers only have day-tickets, some people will work on multiple projects with multiple teams over the weekend. It'll depend on the projects and teams however whether they can accommodate late members. Be sure to join at least join one team before coming on the weekend. At times we'll check in with the teams and have little presentation rounds to see where everyone's at and make sure no-one is stuck.</p>
                    <p>During a final round of presentations every team will get to show off and discuss their project. Though participation in Make.01 is primarily for self-fulfilment, several Raspberry Pis have been made available to be awarded to the most successful project. Success if a popularity contest! Participants get to vote for their favourite project.</p>
                    <p>Check out the <a href="#schedule">schedule</a> for a more detailed run-down of the catalyst night and the Make.01 weekend.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>
